    • classGenerator

      private void classGenerator(Class<?> clazz, String keyWord, String newClassName, String extendedClassName, BufferedWriter writer) throws IOException
      Generates clazz realization to a file which handled by writer.
      Parameters:
      clazz - Class of the class whose implementation should be generated.
      keyWord - string value of keyword implements or extends depends on what program generate.
      newClassName - name of the class where clazz realization should be generated.
      extendedClassName - Class.getCanonicalName() of the class which realization should be generated.
      writer - BufferedWriter which handles file where realization will be written (file name of this file must match with newClassName).
      Throws:
      IOException - if something wrong while writing to file.

      public void implementJar(Class<?> token, Path jarFile) throws ImplerException

    • implement

      public void implement(Class<?> token, Path root) throws ImplerException
      Description copied from interface: Impler
      Produces code implementing class or interface specified by provided token.

      Generated class' name should be the same as the class name of the type token with Impl suffix added. Generated source code should be placed in the correct subdirectory of the specified root directory and have correct file name. For example, the implementation of the interface List should go to $root/java/util/ListImpl.java

      Specified by:
      implement in interface Impler
      Parameters:
      token - type token to create implementation for.
      root - root directory.
      Throws:
      ImplerException - when implementation cannot be generated.

    • main

      public static void main(String[] args)
      Creates an Implementor and runs it depending on the arguments provided.

      If there are two arguments, runs the implement(Class, Path) method, converting the provided argument to a class using the Class.forName(String) method and resolving provided working directory as the path.

      If there are three arguments and the first one equals to "-jar", runs the implementJar(Class, Path) method, converting the second argument to a class using the Class.forName(String) method and the third argument to a path using the Path.of(String, String...) method.

      If the arguments are incorrect or an error occurs during implementation an error message is printed.

      Parameters:
      args - the provided arguments.
